    <text id="B1222T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Schilling gives information about an unnamed woman who was once a slave in
                    Staunton, owned by James Trotter. The Bureau correspondence regarding this case
                    revolves around an effort to find employment for her in Staunton, so that she
                    can move there, but Tukey claims that there are no jobs to be found at
                present.</p>
            </div1>
            <div1 type="section" id="wrapper">
                <p>Bureau <abbr expan="Refugees, Freedmen and Abandoned Lands">R.F. and
                        A.L.</abbr><lb/><abbr expan="Headquaters">Hd.Qrs.</abbr>
                    <abbr expan="Assistant Commissioner">Asst. Comr.</abbr> State of
                    Va.<lb/>Richmond, <abbr expan="February">Feb.</abbr> 23, 1866<lb/><abbr
                        expan="Respectfully">Respty</abbr> referred to <abbr expan="Captain">Capt.</abbr>
                    <hi rend="underline">W.S. How</hi>
                    <abbr expan="Superintendent">Supt</abbr> 6th <abbr expan="District">Dist.</abbr>
                    Va. to know if the woman can find employment at Staunton, if she be furnished
                    transportation to that point.<lb/>By order of <abbr expan="Colonel">Col.</abbr>
                    Brown, James A. Bates<lb/><abbr expan="Captain">Capt.</abbr> and <abbr
                        expan="Acting Assistant Adjutant General">A.A.A.G.</abbr></p>

                <p>Winchester, <abbr expan="Virginia">Va</abbr>
                    <abbr expan="March">Mar</abbr> 3rd/66<lb/>Respectfully referred to Mr. F.S.
                    Tukey <abbr expan="Assistant Superintendent">Asst Supt</abbr> at Staunton, who,
                    if this woman can be employed there will notify <abbr expan="Colonel"
                    >Col.</abbr> Brown to that effect by forwarding direct this communication, if
                        <del rend="none" hand="h1"/> it.<lb/>W. Storer How, <del rend="none" hand="h1"/></p>

                <p>Staunton, Va. <abbr expan="March">Mch</abbr> 5th<lb/><abbr expan="Respectfully"
                        >Resy</abbr> returned<lb/>If is impossible for the woman referred to within
                    to get employment at this place as there is not work for more than two thirds of
                    those who are here at the present time with large families.<lb/>F.S.
                        Tukey<lb/><abbr expan="Assistant Superintendent">Asst. Supt.</abbr><lb/>Sub
                        <abbr expan="District">Dist.</abbr> B</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d5">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d6">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">James A. Bates <abbr expan="Esquire">Esqr.</abbr></name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1866-02-15">15 February 1866.</date>
                        <name type="place">Parkersburg, <abbr expan="West Virginia">W. Va</abbr></name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Sir,</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>In reply to yours of 7th inst. I beg to inform you that the last Master of the
                        <abbr expan="colored">Colord</abbr> woman and family in question lived in
                    Staunton <orig reg="Virginia">W. Va.</orig> and named James Trotter.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>I am Sir<lb/>very respectfully</salute>
                    <signed>James Schilling</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
